<font color="#FF0000">RESPECT</font><br>
<tt>Thu Dec 19  3:29:55 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
Coming back from the 'Nam in late 69 I didn't really expect<br>
the sort of treatment my Dad got after WWII or Korea. But,<br>
I also didn't expect the crowd at SFO airport who massed up<br>
to spit on us.  As I then started College, College stopped. <br>
(1970). Students and Professors suddenly discovered that there was a War going on.  Again, I was chased around campus, spit on and (mildly) beat up by crowds of &quot;peaceful&quot;<br>
students.  I was a Combat Medic, Drafted, Enlisted, Spc5.<br>
Not exactly a policy maker.  I had been against the War<br>
since the early 60's.  Saying all this had no effect on the<br>
crowds.  &quot;I don't get no respect&quot;.  (Well, the MD/PhD I've<br>
earned since does).  To this day, it's Civilians who trigger<br>
bad memories...&quot;what was your lottery number&quot; (Huh?  I just<br>
got drafted). If I'm lucky there will be an older person<br>
around who'll point out that in 1967 there was no lottery.<br>
When asked for stories, ones that bring tears to my eyes<br>
cause yawns.  I guess I'm not Rambo enough.  Bronze, Silver,<br>
and a Purple Heart with Oak Leaves don't make it these days.<br>

